<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="faq">
 <div class="faq-inner">
  <div class="section-tag">Common Questions</div>
  <h2 class="section-heading">Smart Home FAQs</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
   <h3>Lutron or Rako &mdash; which is better?</h3>
   <p>Both are premium wired-RF systems and both are excellent. Lutron RA2 Select / RadioRA is the more recognised global brand with strong reliability and a wide range of compatible drivers. Rako is the UK favourite, designed and supported in Britain, with arguably better integration with non-Lutron mains-dimmable LED drivers. For a typical Somerset home we usually recommend Rako on the basis of price and local support, but specify Lutron where the client already has Lutron elsewhere or wants the very widest third-party compatibility.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
   <h3>Hue bulbs vs smart switches &mdash; what's the difference?</h3>
   <p>Hue bulbs are the easy retrofit: change the bulb, install the bridge, done. The catch is you must leave the wall switch always on, otherwise the bulbs lose power. Smart switches (Lightwave RF, Lutron, Rako, Shelly behind a normal switch) replace or sit behind the existing wall switch &mdash; so the wall switch still works exactly as before AND can be controlled remotely. Smart switches are the more elegant solution but require an electrician; smart bulbs are DIY-friendly but limit you to one circuit.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
   <h3>Do I need new wiring for a smart home?</h3>
   <p>Usually no, especially with wireless RF systems (Hue, Lightwave RF, Aqara, Rako wireless). For wired Lutron RA2 or wired Rako with dedicated controllers and dimmer modules, additional cabling is sometimes needed but we can often retrofit using existing switch drops. We assess this on the site survey. Most retrofits are done without lifting floors.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
   <h3>Will it work with Alexa, Google or Siri?</h3>
   <p>Yes. All major systems we install (Lutron, Rako, Hue, Lightwave RF, Tado, Hive) support Amazon Alexa and Google Assistant. Apple HomeKit / Siri compatibility varies &mdash; Hue, Aqara, Lutron Caseta and certain Lightwave bridges support HomeKit natively; Rako has HomeKit via its bridge (HUB-WCM-PRO). We confirm HomeKit support model-by-model rather than promising it blanket. Voice setup is included in your install.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
   <h3>What is a neutral wire and why does it matter for smart switches?</h3>
   <p>A neutral is the return wire that completes a lighting circuit. Older UK homes commonly only have line and switched-line at the wall switch, with no neutral pulled to the switch position. Most modern smart switches need a neutral to power their internal radio. We check this during the survey &mdash; where there's no neutral, we either pull one in (best), use a neutral-free smart switch (Lutron Caseta, certain Shelly modules, Lightwave with capacitor), or fit a smart relay behind the switch backbox instead.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
   <h3>What happens if my Wi-Fi or internet drops?</h3>
   <p>Properly installed, a smart home keeps working when the internet drops &mdash; the lights still respond to wall switches and keypads because the control system runs on its own RF or wired network locally. App and voice control go offline until connectivity returns. Cheap app-only ecosystems can fail completely without internet, which is why we install proper systems with local control: Lutron, Rako, and HomeKit-paired devices all keep working offline.</p>
  </div>
 </div>
</section>

